<docinfo:dpsi id-string="05CC"/><docinfo:doc-heading>PART 29 TRIALS [rr 29.1&#x2013;29.16] 2 of 2</docinfo:doc-heading><docinfo:doc-id>UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT29_2</docinfo:doc-id><docinfo:doc-lang lang="en"/><docinfo:doc-country iso-cc="AU"/><docinfo:hier><docinfo:hierlev role="ancestor"><heading><title>Uniform Civil Procedure Rules 2005 (NSW)</title></heading><docinfo:hierlev role="ancestor"><heading><title>UNIFORM CIVIL PROCEDURE RULES 2005</title></heading><docinfo:hierlev role="me"><heading><title>PART 29 TRIALS [rr 29.1&#x2013;29.16] 2 of 2</title></heading></docinfo:hierlev></docinfo:hierlev></docinfo:hierlev></docinfo:hier><docinfo:bookseqnum>50010850</docinfo:bookseqnum><docinfo:lbu-meta><docinfo:metaitem name="lbu-sourcename" value="Ritchie's Uniform Civil Procedure NSW"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-docid" value="UCPN.UCPR"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-filename" value="ucpr.xml"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-docid" value="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05"/><docinfo:metaitem name="parent-filename" value="ucpr1002.xml"/></docinfo:lbu-meta><docinfo:selector>legislation</docinfo:selector><docinfo:selector>court-rules</docinfo:selector><docinfo:topiccodes><docinfo:topiccode>#PA#CODE#</docinfo:topiccode></docinfo:topiccodes></docinfo><leg:body><leg:info><leg:juris ln.user-displayed="false" searchtype="LEGISLATION">NSW</leg:juris><leg:officialname ln.user-displayed="false" searchtype="LEGISLATION">UNIFORM CIVIL PROCEDURE RULES 2005</leg:officialname></leg:info><leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.BODY"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rule" searchtype="LEGISLATION RULE"><leg:levelbody><leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT29"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="part" searchtype="LEGISLATION PART" subdoc="false" toc-caption="PART 29 TRIALS [rr 29.1&#x2013;29.16]"><leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-11"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 29.11] r 29.11 Judgment despite verdict, finding or assessment (cf SCR Part 34, rule 8A) ">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-11" type="ext"/>[r 29.11]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Judgment despite verdict, finding or assessment (cf SCR Part 34, rule 8A) </title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>29.11</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>If, at a trial with a jury, a verdict is given or a finding or assessment is made, the court may give judgment as it thinks fit despite the verdict, finding or assessment.</text></p>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT29.R11.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.29-11-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[29.11.5] Receiving jury&#x2019;s verdict"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.29-11-5" type="ext"/>[29.11.5] </edpnum><title>Receiving jury&#x2019;s verdict</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The purpose of this rule is to permit a trial judge to take a jury&#x2019;s verdict notwithstanding an objection of law so that the verdict is available if the judgment is reversed on appeal. Its purpose is not to enable the Court of Appeal to give a judgment contrary to the verdict: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007777" spanref="cr007777-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC9002334"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Field v Timber Industries Ltd</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007777-001"> (NSWCA, Kirby P, Clarke, Meagher JJA, No 644/88, 7 June 1990, unreported, BC9002334)</ci:span></citefragment></ci:content></ci:cite>; <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseinfo><ci:decisiondate year="1990"/></ci:caseinfo><ci:caseref ID="cr007778" spanref="cr007778-001" status="unval"><ci:reporter value="LGRA"/><ci:volume num="72"/><ci:page num="60"/></ci:caseref><ci:caseref ID="cr007779" spanref="cr007779-002"><ci:reporter value="MVR"/><ci:volume num="12"/><ci:page num="321"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Turner v Ku-ring-gai Municipal Council</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> <ci:span spanid="cr007778-001" status="unval">(1990) 72 LGRA 60</ci:span>; <ci:span spanid="cr007779-002">12 MVR 321</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="25453" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>. The rule permits the court to receive a jury&#x2019;s verdict even after determining that the jury should be discharged: <ci:cite searchtype="CASE-REF"><ci:case><ci:caseref ID="cr007780" spanref="cr007780-001"><ci:reporter value="urj"/><ci:refnum num="BC200304434"/></ci:caseref></ci:case><ci:content><citefragment searchtype="CASE-NAME-REF"><emph typestyle="it">Reading v Australian Broadcasting Corp</emph></citefragment><citefragment searchtype="CASE-CITE-REF"> [2003] NSWSC 716; <ci:span spanid="cr007780-001"> BC200304434</ci:span></citefragment> <remotelink dpsi="0018" refpt="366959" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID"><inlineobject alttext="Click for CaseBase entry" attachment="web-server" filename="cbcc.gif" type="image"/></remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite> (jury delivering inexplicably inconsistent answers to questions).</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-12"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 29.12] r 29.12 Death of party before judgment (cf SCR Part 34, rule 10)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-12" type="ext"/>[r 29.12]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Death of party before judgment (cf SCR Part 34, rule 10)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>29.12</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-12.1"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-12.1" type="ext"/>(1)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>If a party dies after the verdict or finding on the questions of fact, the court may give judgment, and judgment may be entered, despite the death.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-12.2"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="subrul" searchtype="LEGISLATION SUBRUL">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><desig><designum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-12.2" type="ext"/>(2)</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>Subrule (1) does not limit the court&#x2019;s power to make orders for the joinder, removal or re-arrangement of parties under Part 6.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:bodytext>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTE"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT29.R12.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTE</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.29-12-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[29.12.5] The court &#x201c;may&#x201d;">
<glp:note><blockquote><hrule/>
<p>
<text><inlineobject attachment="web-server" filename="leg1.gif" type="image"/> Legislation cited in [29.12.5] below. LawNow subscribers click through for daily updates and historical versions.</text><text> </text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_REG_1970-1" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Supreme Court Rules 1970</remotelink> r 29.12(1).</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
</p></blockquote></glp:note><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.29-12-5" type="ext"/>[29.12.5] </edpnum><title>The court &#x201c;may&#x201d;</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Before an order is made under 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="05CC" refpt="UCPN.UCPR.SCR70.R29-12.1" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID" status="unval">r 29.12(1)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 it will be usual for there to be some material to show that the successor or representative of the deceased party has been notified of the application for the entry of judgment.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-13"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 29.13] r 29.13 Record of trial to be kept (cf SCR Part 34, rule 9; DCR Part 26, rule 8A) ">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-13" type="ext"/>[r 29.13]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Record of trial to be kept (cf SCR Part 34, rule 9; DCR Part 26, rule 8A) </title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>29.13</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The associate, or other officer of the court present at the trial, is to maintain and complete a record of the trial.</text></p>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-14"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 29.14] r 29.14 Court may refuse to hear proceedings if fees unpaid (cf Supreme Court Regulation 2000, clause 12; District Court Regulation 2000, clause 9A)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-14" type="ext"/>[r 29.14]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Court may refuse to hear proceedings if fees unpaid (cf Supreme Court Regulation 2000, clause 12; District Court Regulation 2000, clause 9A)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>29.14</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The court may refuse to hear, or to continue to hear, proceedings in respect of which a hearing allocation fee or hearing fee remains due and unpaid.</text></p>
<leg:histnote>
<p><text>[r 29.14  am Amendment 1 of 2005 r 3 and Sch 1[31], effective 15 August 2005]</text></p></leg:histnote>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-15"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 29.15] r 29.15 Statement in open court about settled defamation proceedings (cf SCR Part 67, rule 21; DCR Part 49, rule 19)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-15" type="ext"/>[r 29.15]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Statement in open court about settled defamation proceedings (cf SCR Part 67, rule 21; DCR Part 49, rule 19)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>29.15</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>With the leave of the court, a party to proceedings for defamation that have been settled may make in open court such statement about the proceedings as has been approved by the court in private.</text></p>
<leg:histnote>
<p><text>[r 15  insrt Amendment 5 of 2005  r 3 and Sch 1[6], effective 1 January 2006]</text></p></leg:histnote>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
<leg:level id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-16"><leg:level-vrnt leveltype="rul" searchtype="LEGISLATION RUL" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[r 29.16] r 29.16 Offers to make amends for defamatory publications: determination of questions (cf SCR Part 67, rule 22; DCR Part 49, rule 20)">
<leg:levelinfo>
<leg:levelstatus isrepealed="false" ln.user-displayed="false"/></leg:levelinfo>
<leg:heading inline="true"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.R29-16" type="ext"/>[r 29.16]</edpnum><title searchtype="RUL-TITLE">Offers to make amends for defamatory publications: determination of questions (cf SCR Part 67, rule 22; DCR Part 49, rule 20)</title><desig searchtype="RUL-NUM"><designum>29.16</designum></desig></leg:heading>
<leg:levelbody>
<leg:bodytext>
<p><text>The court may hear an application and determine any question under 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="006O" refpt="DEF.NSWLEG.DA.S9F.2" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">section 9F(2)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 of the Defamation Act 1974 or 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="006O" refpt="DEF.NSWLEG.DAN05.S15.3" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">section 15(3)</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 of the Defamation Act 2005 in the absence of the public.</text></p>
<leg:histnote>
<p><text>[r 16  insrt Amendment 5 of 2005  r 3 and Sch 1[6], effective 1 January 2006]</text></p></leg:histnote>
<leg:comntry subdoc="true" toc-caption="NOTES"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><title><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.UCPRN05.PT29.R16.COM1" type="ext"/>NOTES</title></heading>
<level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.29-16-5" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[29.16.5] Defence of offer of amends"><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.29-16-5" type="ext"/>[29.16.5] </edpnum><title>Defence of offer of amends</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>Part 3 Division 1 of the Defamation Act 2005 and Part 2A of the Defamation Act 1974 deal with resolution of disputes by way of offers of amends. Offers are deemed to be made without prejudice, unless the offer otherwise provides. Failure to accept an offer of amends provides a complete defence to the action if the offer is reasonable, made as soon as practicable after the publisher is made aware of the alleged defamatory meaning, and is one that the publisher is willing and able to perform: s 18 of the Defamation Act 2005 and s 9G of the Defamation Act 1974. The court may determine any question that arises in relation to implementation of the offer, including assessment of the amount of compensation to be paid under an offer: see s 15 of the Defamation Act 2005 and s 9F of the Defamation Act 1974.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level><level id="UCPN_UCPR.SGM_UCPN.UCPR.29-16-10" leveltype="para0" subdoc="true" toc-caption="[29.16.10] Indemnity costs">
<glp:note><blockquote><hrule/>
<p>
<text><inlineobject attachment="web-server" filename="leg1.gif" type="image"/> Legislation cited in [29.16.10] below. LawNow subscribers click through for daily updates and historical versions.</text><text> </text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_ACT_2005-77" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Defamation Act 2005</remotelink> s 40.</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
<text>(NSW) <ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink alttext="Click to link to LawNow Legislation" dpsi="005Y" refpt="NSW_ACT_1974-18" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">Defamation Act 1974</remotelink> s 48A.</ci:content></ci:cite></text>
</p></blockquote></glp:note><heading searchtype="COMMENTARY"><edpnum><refpt id="UCPN.UCPR.29-16-10" type="ext"/>[29.16.10] </edpnum><title>Indemnity costs</title></heading>
<bodytext searchtype="COMMENTARY">
<p>
<text>The court must order indemnity costs unless the interests of justice require otherwise in circumstances where an unsuccessful party unreasonably failed to make or to agree to a settlement offer which includes an offer to make amends: 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="006O" refpt="DEF.NSWLEG.DAN05.S40" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">s 40</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 of the Defamation Act 2005 and 
<ci:cite searchtype="LEG-REF"><ci:content><remotelink dpsi="006O" refpt="DEF.NSWLEG.DA.S48A" remotekey1="REFPTID" service="DOC-ID">s 48A</remotelink></ci:content></ci:cite>
 of the Defamation Act 1974.</text></p>
</bodytext>
</level></leg:comntry>
</leg:bodytext>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
</leg:level>
</leg:levelbody>
</leg:level-vrnt>
